Package fr.univartois.cril.approximation.util.collections.maps

Class MapDoubleAdapter<K>

java.lang.Object
fr.univartois.cril.approximation.util.collections.maps.MapDoubleAdapter<K>
Type Parameters:
K - The type of the keys.
All Implemented Interfaces:
MapDouble<K>, Iterable<MapDouble.Entry<K>>
public final class MapDoubleAdapter<K> extends Object implements MapDouble<K>
The MapDoubleAdapter adapts a Map to a MapDouble.

More formally, returns true if and only if this map contains at least one mapping to a value v such that Double.compare(value, v) == 0.     • putAll

      public void putAll(MapDouble<? extends K> map)
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Copies all of the mappings from the specified map to this map (optional operation). The effect of this call is equivalent to that of calling put(k, v) on this map once for each mapping from key k to value v in the specified map. The behavior of this operation is undefined if the specified map is modified while the operation is in progress.

    • remove

      public OptionalDouble remove(Object key)
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Removes the mapping for a key from this map if it is present (optional operation). More formally, if this map contains a mapping from key k to value v such that Objects.equals(key, k), that mapping is removed. The map can contain at most one such mapping.

      Returns the value to which this map previously associated the key, or OptionalDouble.empty() if the map contained no mapping for the key.

      The map will not contain a mapping for the specified key once the call returns.

      Specified by:
      remove in interface MapDouble<K>
      Parameters:
      key - The key whose mapping is to be removed from the map.
      Returns:
      The previous value associated with key, or OptionalDouble.empty() if there was no mapping for key.

    • keySet

      public Set<K> keySet()
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Returns a Set view of the keys contained in this map. The set is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the set, and vice-versa. If the map is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress (except through the iterator's own remove operation), the results of the iteration are undefined. The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map, via the remove, removeAll, retainAll, and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations.
      Specified by:
      keySet in interface MapDouble<K>
      Returns:
      A set view of the keys contained in this map.

      public Set<MapDouble.Entry<K>> entrySet()
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Returns a Set view of the mappings contained in this map. The set is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the set, and vice-versa. If the map is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress (except through the iterator's own remove operation, or through the setValue operation on a map entry returned by the iterator) the results of the iteration are undefined. The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding mapping from the map, via the remove, removeAll, retainAll and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations.

      public int hashCode()
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Returns the hash code value for this map. The hash code of a map is defined to be the sum of the hash codes of each entry in the map's entrySet() view. This ensures that m1.equals(m2) implies that m1.hashCode() == m2.hashCode() for any two maps m1 and m2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode().

      public boolean equals(Object object)
      Description copied from interface: MapDouble
      Compares the specified object with this map for equality. Returns true if the given object is also a map and the two maps represent the same mappings. More formally, two maps m1 and m2 represent the same mappings if m1.entrySet().equals(m2.entrySet()). This ensures that the equals method works properly across different implementations of the MapDouble interface.
